AboutAbout

Graduated with a master's degree in mathematics and computer science applied to human sciences, I have skills to help companies and institutions in decision making. I master both statistical and econometric tools and data processing, but also have economic knowledge essential to the realization of sectorial studies or evaluation of public policies.

I have been able to acquire and deepen the following skills during my training and experiences :
☑ Mastery of statistical, econometric and data processing methods
☑ Mastery of statistical and econometric software tools (R, Access, Excel, SAS) as well as specialized professional solutions (Analyzer)
☑ Good knowledge of economic analysis tools for markets, sectors and territories in which companies and institutions operate.

I have also acquired a number of non-technical skills that have helped me progress in my professional and private life. As a result, I was also able to manage a departmental project in my previous position :
☑ Project organization
☑ Excellent communication and coaching skills
☑ English B2 level

I also have a B permit and a vehicle.


To contact me :

    Thank you hashtag #TNW2022 for selecting me for the top 500 digital minds under the age of 26!

    A little over a year ago, I started the exciting journey of entrepreneurship with the start-up OASYS NOW.
    I am fascinated by the impact of technological innovation on scientific discovery, specifically in my field Nanobiology.

    The start-up enables me to bring cutting edge technology and scientific advancements to society, by building an ethical-by-design storage and exchange platform for DNA.

    Looking forward to meeting the other T499 at hashtag #TNWConference on June 16th and 17th!

    hashtag #T500
  • PostPost
    In November I successfully presented my BSc thesis on an optimized normalization procedure for Differential Expression analysis of RNA-sequencing, receiving a 9 for my complete project. This is however not the end of this project, as I will start working full time for the Ageing Lab of Joris Pothof, Department of Moleculair Genetics, Erasmus MC to publish my research.

    The Nanobiology programme has equipped me with the right tools to investigate the impact of biological biases on technical tools and mathematical models. I researched the technical and biological bias induced by the varying gene length compositions of ageing tissues. I also produced a method that alleviated this gene length bias, uncovering many more significantly found Differentially Expressed genes.

    I would like to thank Joris Pothof and my daily supervisor Jiang Chang for giving me the opportunity to work on this project.

AboutAbout

Electrical Engineering Master student at Delft Technical University.

Perfectionism and creative way of solving complex problems motivate me to self-improve and enhance the world around.

Electrical Engineering Bachelor at Hanze UAS contained various research and practical projects that contributed to my professional and personal development. I gained experience in robotics, energy, medical, agricultural and environmental system development.

Besides the regular study, I participated in the Honours Talent Programme. It is an extra international course for students who tend to do more. I had an opportunity to work in multidisciplinary project groups to solve companies/society problems. Within this period, I researched Power-to-Gas technology, worked as a marketing manager, researched Microfinance problems, analysed companies' claims, etc.

As graduation thesis, I researched and developed a control system for an autonomous collaborative robot using advanced image processing algorithms.

To enhance Control Systems, Signal Processing and Mathematics skills, I worked as a student assistant for 1st, 2nd and 3rd-year students.   • Sixth-Order Adaptive Non-uniform Grids for Singularly Perturbed Boundary Value ProblemsSixth-Order Adaptive Non-uniform Grids for Singularly Perturbed Boundary Value Problems
    Numerical Geometry, Grid Generation and Scientific Computing, Springer · Oct 11, 2019Numerical Geometry, Grid Generation and Scientific Computing, Springer · Oct 11, 2019
    • Show publication
      • In this paper, a sixth order adaptive non-uniform grid has been developed for solving a singularly perturbed boundary-value problem (SPBVP) with boundary layers. For this SPBVP with a small parameter in the leading derivative, an adaptive finite difference method based on the equidistribution principle, is adopted to establish 6th order of convergence. To achieve this supra-convergence, we study the truncation error of the discretized system and obtain an optimal adaptive non-uniform grid. Considering a second order three-point central finite-difference scheme, we develop sixth order approximations by a suitable choice of the underlying optimal adaptive grid. Further, we apply this optimal adaptive grid to nonlinear SPBVPs, by using an extra approximations of the nonlinear term and we obtain almost 6th order of convergence. Unlike other adaptive non-uniform grids, our strategy uses no pre-knowledge of the location and width of the layers. We also show that other choices of the grid distributions lead to a substantial degradation of the accuracy. Numerical results illustrate the effectiveness of the proposed higher order adaptive numerical strategy for both linear and nonlinear SPBVPs.In this paper, a sixth order adaptive non-uniform grid has been developed for solving a singularly perturbed boundary-value problem (SPBVP) with boundary layers. For this SPBVP with a small parameter in the leading derivative, an adaptive finite difference method based on the equidistribution principle, is adopted to establish 6th order of convergence. To achieve this supra-convergence, we study the truncation error of the discretized system and obtain an optimal adaptive non-uniform grid. Considering a second order three-point central finite-difference scheme, we develop sixth order approximations by a suitable choice of the underlying optimal adaptive grid. Further, we apply this optimal adaptive grid to nonlinear SPBVPs, by using an extra approximations of the nonlinear term and we obtain almost 6th order of convergence. Unlike other adaptive non-uniform grids, our strategy uses no pre-knowledge of the location and width of the layers. We also show that other choices of the grid distributions lead to a substantial degradation of the accuracy. Numerical results illustrate the effectiveness of the proposed higher order adaptive numerical strategy for both linear and nonlinear SPBVPs.
  • A numerical study of the higher-dimensional Gelfand-Bratu modelA numerical study of the higher-dimensional Gelfand-Bratu model
    Computers & Mathematics with Applications, Elsevier · Oct 9, 2019Computers & Mathematics with Applications, Elsevier · Oct 9, 2019
    • Show publication
      • In this article, a higher dimensional nonlinear boundary-value problem, viz., Gelfand-Bratu (GB) problem, is solved numerically. For the three-dimensional case, we present an accurate and efficient nonlinear multigrid (MG) approach and investigate multiplicities depending on the bifurcation parameter λ. We adopt a nonlinear MG approach Full approximation scheme (FAS) extended with a Krylov method as a smoother to handle the computational difficulties for obtaining the upper branches of the solutions. Further, we examine the numerical bifurcation behaviour of the GB problem in 3D and identify the existence of two new bifurcation points. Experiments illustrate the convergence of the numerical solutions and demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed numerical strategy for all parameter values λ∈(0,λc]. For higher dimensions, we transform the GB problem, using n-dimensional spherical coordinates, to a nonlinear ordinary differential equation (ODE). The numerical solutions of this nonlinear ODE are computed by a shooting method for a range of values of the dimension parameter n. Numerical experiments show the existence of several types of solutions for different values of n and λ. These results confirm the bifurcation behaviour of the higher dimensional GB problem as predicted from theoretical results in literature.In this article, a higher dimensional nonlinear boundary-value problem, viz., Gelfand-Bratu (GB) problem, is solved numerically. For the three-dimensional case, we present an accurate and efficient nonlinear multigrid (MG) approach and investigate multiplicities depending on the bifurcation parameter λ. We adopt a nonlinear MG approach Full approximation scheme (FAS) extended with a Krylov method as a smoother to handle the computational difficulties for obtaining the upper branches of the solutions. Further, we examine the numerical bifurcation behaviour of the GB problem in 3D and identify the existence of two new bifurcation points. Experiments illustrate the convergence of the numerical solutions and demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed numerical strategy for all parameter values λ∈(0,λc]. For higher dimensions, we transform the GB problem, using n-dimensional spherical coordinates, to a nonlinear ordinary differential equation (ODE). The numerical solutions of this nonlinear ODE are computed by a shooting method for a range of values of the dimension parameter n. Numerical experiments show the existence of several types of solutions for different values of n and λ. These results confirm the bifurcation behaviour of the higher dimensional GB problem as predicted from theoretical results in literature.

AboutAbout

I am passionate about developing practical/novel AI based solutions to business problems. I have channelled my passion into a PhD and worked on:
• novel data augmentation and feature engineering methods to boost forecasting accuracies of machine learning models,
• novel deep reinforcement learning methods to improve the performance of risk-constrained trading strategies.

Moreover, during my PhD, I have supervised BSc and MSc students with AI-based projects, such as bidding strategies for storage devices using transformer-based deep reinforcement learning.

I have enjoyed building a bridge between industry and academia by collaborating with Scholt Energy during my PhD and Moody’s Analytics during my MSc.

From Mathematics to Philosophy, my colourful background has widened my perspective and improved my critical thinking and problem-solving skills. I constantly seek to improve myself, e.g. my knowledge in machine learning, and my skills in leadership and Dutch. Please do not hesitate to contact me if you would like to have a chat.

PublicationsPublications

  • Statistical arbitrage trading on the intraday market using the asynchronous advantage actor–critic methodStatistical arbitrage trading on the intraday market using the asynchronous advantage actor–critic method
    Applied Energy · May 15, 2022Applied Energy · May 15, 2022
    • Show publication
      • In this paper, we focus on statistical arbitrage trading opportunities involving the continuous exploitation of price differences arising during an intraday trading period with the option of closing positions on the balancing market. We aim to maximise the reward–risk ratio of an autonomous trading strategy. To find an optimal trading policy, we propose utilising the asynchronous advantage actor–critic (A3C) algorithm, a deep reinforcement learning method, with function approximators of two-headed shared deep neural networks. We enforce a risk-constrained trading strategy by limiting the maximum allowed position, and conduct state engineering and selection processes. We introduce a novel reward function and goal-based exploration, i.e. behaviour cloning. Our methodology is evaluated on a case study using the limit order book of the European single intraday coupled market (SIDC) available for the Dutch market area. The majority of hourly products on the test set return a profit. We expect our study to benefit electricity traders, renewable electricity producers and researchers who seek to implement state-of-art intelligent trading strategies.In this paper, we focus on statistical arbitrage trading opportunities involving the continuous exploitation of price differences arising during an intraday trading period with the option of closing positions on the balancing market.   • Data Augmentation for Time Series Regression: Applying Transformations, Autoencoders and Adversarial Networks to Electricity Price ForecastingData Augmentation for Time Series Regression: Applying Transformations, Autoencoders and Adversarial Networks to Electricity Price Forecasting
    Applied Energy · Dec 15, 2021Applied Energy · Dec 15, 2021
    • Show publication
      • A model’s expected generalisation error is inversely proportional to its training set size. This relationship can pose a problem when modelling multivariate time series, because structural breaks, low sampling rates, and high data gathering costs can severely restrict training set sizes, increasing a model’s expected generalisation error by spurring regression model overfitting. Artificially expanding the training set size, using data augmentation methods, can, however, counteract the restrictions imposed by small sample sizes: increasing a model’s robustness to overfitting and boosting out-of-sample prediction accuracies. While existing time series augmentation methods have predominantly utilised feature space transformations to artificially expand training set sizes and boost prediction accuracies, we propose using autoencoders (AEs), variational autoencoders (VAEs) and Wasserstein generative adversarial networks with a gradient penalty (WGAN-GPs) for time series augmentation. To evaluate our proposed augmentors, as a case study we forecast Belgian and Dutch day-ahead electricity market prices using both autoregressive models and artificial neural networks. Overall, our results demonstrate that AEs, VAEs, and WGAN-GPs can significantly boost regression accuracies; on average decreasing benchmark model mean absolute errors by 2.23%, 2.73% and 2.97% respectively. Moreover, our results demonstrate that combining AE, VAE, and WGAN-GP generated time series can further boost regression accuracies; on average decreasing benchmark errors by 3.44%. As our proposed augmentors outperform existing augmentation methods, we strongly believe that both practitioners and researchers aiming to generate time series or reduce time series regression errors will find utility in our study.A model’s expected generalisation error is inversely proportional to its training set size.   • Exploratory Visual Analytics for the European Single Intra-Day Coupled Electricity MarketExploratory Visual Analytics for the European Single Intra-Day Coupled Electricity Market
    2020 International Conference on Smart Energy Systems and Technologies (SEST) · Sep 22, 20202020 International Conference on Smart Energy Systems and Technologies (SEST) · Sep 22, 2020
    • Show publication
      • European single intra-day coupled electricity market (SIDC) trading activity has increased substantially in recent years mainly as a consequence of the increasing penetration of renewable energy production and its subsequent impact on imbalance market prices. Nonetheless, more research is needed to understand this growing market. This paper presents exploratory visual analytics tools for tradable contracts of the SIDC. The main visualisations are created from order and trade books and intended to increase our domain knowledge of the SIDC by monitoring market trends, behaviours, depth, price consensus and liquidity. Furthermore, previous contracts of SIDC volumes and balancing prices are visualised to identify trading opportunities and risks. We expect that the presented visual analytics will be useful for both practitioners and researchers seeking quick and easily implementable tools for acquiring additional market insights and developing manual or automated trading strategies.European single intra-day coupled electricity market (SIDC) trading activity has increased substantially in recent years mainly as a consequence of the increasing penetration of renewable energy production and its subsequent impact on imbalance market prices. Nonetheless, more research is needed to understand this growing market. This paper presents exploratory visual analytics tools for tradable contracts of the SIDC. The main visualisations are created from order and trade books and intended to increase our domain knowledge of the SIDC by monitoring market trends, behaviours, depth, price consensus and liquidity. Furthermore, previous contracts of SIDC volumes and balancing prices are visualised to identify trading opportunities and risks. We expect that the presented visual analytics will be useful for both practitioners and researchers seeking quick and easily implementable tools for acquiring additional market insights and developing manual or automated trading strategies.

AboutAbout

I recently graduated from the University of Amsterdam with a master's degree in Logic. Previously, I obtained a bachelor's degree in Mathematics at Humboldt University, Berlin.

During my Mathematics studies, I specialized in the abstract field of topology and geometry. To gain application-related insights, I supplemented my academic studies with Computer Science and Data Science classes and completed two data-oriented internships. This included data analysis with SQL and data exploration and prediction using machine learning techniques in R.

The Master of Logic at the ILLC lies at the interface between Mathematics, Computer Science, Philosophy and Linguistics. I very much enjoyed learning how formal (logical) systems can be used in collective decision-making, AI, psychology, law and other disciplines. Therefore, I am trained to work with convoluted structures and to solve complex problems.

Using abstract ideas for solving real world problems intrigues me. AboutAbout

How does the form of communication effect what is it possible to communicate? Understanding the answer to this question allows us to be more effective in nearly any situation. This awareness becomes particularly important in situations where technical information is at stake.

In the realm of formal logic, this question formed the guidance to my research, but its application is much wider. Understanding the possibilities--and limitations -- of communication helps us understand and approach problems on a very practical level.

From my experience reconceptualizing the world through the eyes of another culture, to re-imagining a familiar concept through the perspective of a mathematics student, each interaction turns on the information exchanged. However, but just as important, is our ability to capture that information.

This experience makes me comfortable equally in a technical, rule-based setting, as it does in a setting where that technicality must be presented in an accessible format to those less familiar.

I'm passionate about discovering and developing new ideas, and about finding the best way to share them with others.

My background is in mathematics, logic, and philosophy of language. I've had the opportunity to work on multiple research projects within these fields (please email for CV and more details). However, my experience is not limited to the conceptual. I've worked directly with students and academic administrative offices, addressing both content and student acclimation to university life. My international experience has taught me to work with a wide variety of people.

I'm seeking an opportunity to put this experience to work. I enjoy learning and problem-solving, and I work hard. AboutAbout

"A ship in harbor is safe, but that is not what ships are built for" - John A. Shedd

Welcome to my LinkedIn page, my name is Siska de Vreeze. I'm down-to-earth and a little bit stubborn. These characteristics make that I am not afraid to express my opinion, and that I do not blindly follow the masses. I am also eager to learn and I love a challenge.
These traits led me to complete my Bachelor's programme in Civil Engineering with great pleasure and motivation. With my passion for water and hydraulic structures, this programme was the natural choice. After a minor in Luleå, Sweden, and a BSc thesis project at the Ministry of Infrastructure and Water Management, I completed the Bachelor's programme in 2018. After this, I started the Master's programme in Civil Engineering and Management. My specialisation is Water Engineering and Management, with the track River and Coastal Engineering. I completed this programme in the summer of 2020, when I finished my MSc thesis research at Marine Scotland Science in Aberdeen, United Kingdom.
In June 2022, after two years of working as a (geo)hydrologist at the Province of Friesland, I started working at Sweco as an advisor on geohydrology."A ship in harbor is safe, but that is not what ships are built for" - John A.   • Lecturer Lecturer
    FreelanceFreelance Feb 2015 - Nov 2019 · 4 yrs 10 mosFeb 2015 - Nov 2019 · 4 yrs 10 mos Russia, EuropeRussia, Europe
      • Interactive sessions about academic music for non-musicians "Discuss the classics!"

        Since 2015 and till now I am providing interactive sessions about academic music to let people know more about its history and essence and to let them open the emotional and intellectual source of classics for joy and self development.

        During our meetings we listen to prepared fragments of music and discuss what we heard. In the interactive manner of opinion exchange people receive an experience of "active" listening and perception (instead of just following the lecture), as well as free expression of their own opinion, that they do not have in big concert halls, where they are just "guests in the world of classics". The moderator of discussion asks needed questions to pay people attention to some details of sounding material, that are important for this exact topic of current meeting.

        Such format helps to break the barrier between "difficult" music and non prepared audience, to show people and they CAN understand classics and enjoy it without high music education. And it is always a lot of fun! :-)

        Till this moment more than 20 meetings were held in Saint Petersburg, Moscow, Bonn (in Russian and English language). Topics are covering different aspects of music history (e.g. history of music genres and compositional approaches) and music theory (e.g. explanation of music forms, music & words interaction in vocal music). More details can be given by request.

        We are always open to new audience and musicologists, who also want to share knowledge with people. Join us and let`s discover the power of classics together!

AboutAbout

After a five month course in software engineering at the Amsterdam University of Applied Sciences, I have recently joined CGI as a software engineer. At CGI I am combining my improved programming skills with my knowledge and experience in the fields of finance, mathematical modelling and statistics.

Until August 2020, I've worked as an actuary at Nationale Nederlanden Leven. After a year in the Finance department, I was part of the Risk department for four years, where I developed models for longevity risk and longevity hedging. My background is in Applied Mathematics with a specialisation in probability theory and optimisation. Consecutively, I have completed a PhD on Statistical Methods for Anomaly Detection. I started my PhD while working at the research institute TNO, where I applied my knowledge mainly in the fields of Computer Networks and Smart Grids. Apart from mathematics I also have a degree in Italian.

I'm a well-organised, results-oriented and proactive professional with excellent social and analytical skills. During my work, PhD and studies, I further developed skills in programming, modelling, data analysis, presenting, teaching, supervising, editing, team work and project management.After a five month course in software engineering at the Amsterdam University of Applied Sciences, I have recently joined CGI as a software engineer. PublicationsPublications

  • Resource allocation problems with expensive function evaluationsResource allocation problems with expensive function evaluations
    European Journal of Operational Research · Jul 31, 2022European Journal of Operational Research · Jul 31, 2022
    • Show publication
      • The resource allocation problem is among the classical problems in operations research, and has been studied extensively for decades. However, current solution approaches are not able to efficiently handle problems with expensive function evaluations, which can occur in a variety of applications. We study the integer resource allocation problem with expensive function evaluations, for both convex and non-convex separable cost functions. We present several solution methods, both heuristics and exact methods, that aim to limit the number of function evaluations. The methods are compared in numerical experiments using both randomly generated instances and instances from two resource allocation problems occurring in radiation therapy planning. Results show that the presented solution methods compare favorably against existing derivative free optimization solvers.The resource allocation problem is among the classical problems in operations research, and has been studied extensively for decades. However, current solution approaches are not able to efficiently handle problems with expensive function evaluations, which can occur in a variety of applications. We study the integer resource allocation problem with expensive function evaluations, for both convex and non-convex separable cost functions. We present several solution methods, both heuristics and exact methods, that aim to limit the number of function evaluations. The methods are compared in numerical experiments using both randomly generated instances and instances from two resource allocation problems occurring in radiation therapy planning. Results show that the presented solution methods compare favorably against existing derivative free optimization solvers.

  • Dynamic fluence map sequencing using piecewise linear leaf position functionsDynamic fluence map sequencing using piecewise linear leaf position functions
    IOPscience · Jan 18, 2019IOPscience · Jan 18, 2019
    • Show publication
      • Within the setting of intensity modulated radiation therapy (IMRT) and the fully continuous version of IMRT called volumetric modulated radiation therapy (VMAT), we consider the problem of matching a given fluence map as well as possible in limited time by the use of a linear accelerator (linac) with a multi-leaf collimator (MLC). We introduce two modeling strategies to manage the nonconvexity and the associated local minima of this problem. The first is the use of linear splines to model the MLC leaf positions as functions of time. The second is a progressively controllable smooth model (instead of a step function) of how the leaves block the fluence radiation. We propose a two part solution: an outer loop that optimizes the dose rate pattern over time, and an inner loop that given a dose rate pattern optimizes the leaf trajectories.Within the setting of intensity modulated radiation therapy (IMRT) and the fully continuous version of IMRT called volumetric modulated radiation therapy (VMAT), we consider the problem of matching a given fluence map as well as possible in limited time by the use of a linear accelerator (linac) with a multi-leaf collimator (MLC). We introduce two modeling strategies to manage the nonconvexity and the associated local minima of this problem. The first is the use of linear splines to model the MLC leaf positions as functions of time. The second is a progressively controllable smooth model (instead of a step function) of how the leaves block the fluence radiation. We propose a two part solution: an outer loop that optimizes the dose rate pattern over time, and an inner loop that given a dose rate pattern optimizes the leaf trajectories.

AboutAbout

Hi, I’m Parnian!

My entire life and career to date has been in permanent Beta mode; each day for me is an opportunity to learn more, do more and grow more. I’m on a mission to pursue a career where I can help people and communities do the same in alignment with their inner and outer nature.

What excites me most is connecting with different people, cultures, and natures. Furthermore, understanding their relationships and empowering holistic growth by going back to our roots. By being born and raised in Iran, the beautiful cat-shaped land filled with profound nature and culture, and later living in the Netherlands, I have had the privilege of having an enriched experience with living a fulfilled life in line with different communities, cultures, and natures around me while contributing to their growth.

A few pivotal moments along my journey include:

🌱As a project officer in a project with the goal to develop eco-tourism in rural areas of Urmia Lake as an alternative means of livelihood, I used my critical thinking to propose strategies that impacted the targeted rural communities by shifting the project from a top-down development program to a community-based development program.

🌱My desire for learning and evolving led me to move from Iran to the Netherlands to study Place, Culture, and Tourism. During my studies I appliedd my creative problem-solving approach to help my classmates and study program to grow and improve. I ideated, developed, and implemented a career workshop regarding the future of tourism in collaboration with the program director and career advisor.

🌱Most recently I was the program coordinator of Mathematics studies, where I collaborated with my fellow program coordinators to outline and run an improvement plan that thrived on helping teachers and support staff collaborate in a more efficient way. The motivation behind this plan was to create a healthier workplace that embraces individual and team growth while also showcasing a higher-quality program to the students.

In my free time, you find me doing Yoga or Pilates, dancing, experimenting with cooking, deepening my understanding of humanity sciences (especially psychology), and learning about new cultures and backgrounds.

AboutAbout

✨I am a recent Finance MSC graduate, with a bachelors in Economics. My main skills are in Mathematics, Data analysis and collection, Tableau, Economics, Banking and many more ✨
An excited, hands-on, ambitious and determined person with an eager desire to learn and to be challenged.


A bit about Myself 📓

Born and raised in Portugal, I have always considered myself a perseverant person, fighting and working hard to achieve my goals. I am committed, ready-to-act and I pride myself in my analytical skills and my work ethic, which have allowed me to be a great student throughout both my academic oath and to reach all the opportunities I ever dreamed of.

Work Experience 💻

I have had two internships since 2018 which allowed me to develop communication, teamworking and reporting skills very early on, while also allowing me to experience the corporate world fully hands-on. Besides these experiences, I had the opportunity of being a trainee at the European Central Bank while I was finishing my masters, for a one-year traineeship in the Banking Supervision division, as a Credit Risk supervisor. This was a dream experience for me, as I was able to explore an area for which I was always passionate about, Banking, and to work in an extremely international, inclusive institution with a systemic impact in the world.
Besides that, throughout my life I have participated in volunteering projects, of which I am proud to belong to (e.g., Web Summit, helping out speakers, or ReFood collecting and distributing food to those in need).

Where did I study? 📚

In February 2022 I graduated from my Masters in Finance at Católica-Lisbon School of Business and Economics, as a top student (Dean's List 2021). Wrote my thesis on Zombie Firms and their evolution in the Portuguese Corporate Market while working. During my studies, I explored new topics in Banking, Corporate Markets, Valuation and Programming, having worked with Python, VBA and Stata, and developing skills in many visualization tools (mainly Tableau, Excel), amongst other Finance topics.

My bachelors is in Economics from the same university, in Lisbon, where I developed my passion for the banking world and economics-related topics. I was also able to develop my public speaking and leadership skills while studying at Católica due to the participation in both the Student's Association and my role as Head of Operations & Quality at Católica Consulting Linked, a consulting club where I was responsible for a team of 11 people.

AboutAbout

I am a highly driven Maltese student who constantly aims to broaden my knowledge and develop myself as much as possible. From a young age I was intrigued by the vastness of space and our lack of knowledge about it. I am highly ambitious and after seeing that I couldn`t pursue a degree program related to studying and increasing my knowledge on space I was determined to find it elsewhere. Hence, the reason why I decided to pursue a degree program in Astronomy at the University of Groningen in the Netherlands. I am also currently following an Honours program alongside my bachelor’s degree which has introduced me to a vast number of diverse skills and topics, including "Effective Teamwork", "Academic Writing", "The Art of Influence", "Debating" and "Living a balanced life".

Having studied Pure mathematics, physics, biology and chemistry at an advanced level has enabled me to create links between the four disciplines and better understand the way in which the world works. While only mathematics and physics can be said to be directly related to my choice of degree, chemistry and biology allow me to approach the universe in a variety of ways and connect the dots between different scientific phenomena.

I aim to continue broadening my knowledge of astronomy as well as that of biology and chemistry to the side so as to contribute to the interdisciplinary knowledge of the natural sciences. With this knowledge I will then carry out research on the origin of life on Earth, life on other planets and other topics encompassed within the field of Astrobiology.

AboutAbout

I'm driven by a need to learn and understand as much as possible about the scientifical aspects of our universe and the world we live in. To me, one of the most beautiful things in life, is when many different scientifical disciplines are joined together to explain a massive, complicated, and intertwined system. As a result I have a broad range of interests, which are still expanding every day.

I’m a bachelor student in Earth Sciences, a field that strongly agrees with my knowledge seeking nature. In this I found that my interests mostly lie in Planetary Sciences, Geochemistry, Volcanism, Paleontology and Paleogenetics. One of my ambitions is to study extra-terrestrial rock samples and the geology of extra-terrestrial bodies.

When I’m not studying, I tutor high school students in Mathematics and Chemistry. In my free time I like to go hiking or do some painting or reading. People describe me as hardworking, resilient and dedicated. I think it’s important to be thorough in my work. I’m a very independent worker but I’m also a good team-worker and have a natural sense for leadership.

  • A Gentle Sedimentation Process for Size-Selecting Porous Silicon Microparticles to Be Used for Drug Delivery Via Fine Gauge Needle AdministrationA Gentle Sedimentation Process for Size-Selecting Porous Silicon Microparticles to Be Used for Drug Delivery Via Fine Gauge Needle Administration
    Springer Nature · Dec 29, 2020Springer Nature · Dec 29, 2020
    • Show publication
      • Biodegradable porous silicon (pSi) particles are under development for drug delivery applications. The optimum particle size very much depends on medical use, and microparticles can outperform nanoparticles in specific instances. Here we demonstrate the ability of sedimentation to size-select ultrasmall (1–10 μm) nanoporous microparticles in common solvents. Size tunability is quantified for 1–24 h of sedimentation. Experimental values of settling times in ethanol and water are compared to those calculated using Stokes’ Law. Differences can arise due to particle agglomeration, internal gas generation and incomplete wetting. Air-dried and supercritically-dried pSi powders are shown to have, for example, their median diameter d (0.5) particle sizes reduced from 13 to 1 μm and from 20 to 3 μm, using sedimentation times of 6 and 2 h respectively. Such filtered microparticles also have much narrower size distributions and are hence suitable for administration in 27 gauge microneedles, commonly used in intravitreal drug delivery.Biodegradable porous silicon (pSi) particles are under development for drug delivery applications. Such filtered microparticles also have much narrower size distributions and are hence suitable for administration in 27 gauge microneedles, commonly used in intravitreal drug delivery.
  • Preserving surface area and porosity during fabrication of silicon aerocrystal particles from anodized wafersPreserving surface area and porosity during fabrication of silicon aerocrystal particles from anodized wafers
    Journal of Porous materials · Oct 21, 2020Journal of Porous materials · Oct 21, 2020
    • Show publication
      • Porous silicon layers on wafers are commonly converted into particles by mechanical milling or ultrasonic fragmentation. The former technique can rapidly generate large batches of microparticles. The latter technique is commonly used for making nanoparticles but processing times are very long and yields, where reported, are often very low. With both processing techniques, the porosity and surface area of the particles generated are often assumed to be similar to those of the parent film. We demonstrate that this is rarely the case, using air-dried high porosity and supercritically dried aerocrystals as examples. We show that whereas ball milling can more quickly generate much higher yields of particles, it is much more damaging to the nanostructures than ultrasonic fragmentation. The latter technique is particularly promising for silicon aerocrystals since processing times are reduced whilst yields are simultaneously raised with ultrahigh porosity structures. Not only that, but very high surface areas (> 500 m2/g) can be completely preserved with ultrasonic fragmentation.Porous silicon layers on wafers are commonly converted into particles by mechanical milling or ultrasonic fragmentation. The former technique can rapidly generate large batches of microparticles. The latter technique is commonly used for making nanoparticles but processing times are very long and yields, where reported, are often very low. With both processing techniques, the porosity and surface area of the particles generated are often assumed to be similar to those of the parent film. We demonstrate that this is rarely the case, using air-dried high porosity and supercritically dried aerocrystals as examples. We show that whereas ball milling can more quickly generate much higher yields of particles, it is much more damaging to the nanostructures than ultrasonic fragmentation. The latter technique is particularly promising for silicon aerocrystals since processing times are reduced whilst yields are simultaneously raised with ultrahigh porosity structures. Not only that, but very high surface areas (> 500 m2/g) can be completely preserved with ultrasonic fragmentation.
